            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1470058752,
            "creation_date": 1470057562,
            "body": "<p>It would be easier to do a negative match.  That is, look for what is not allowed:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\\\\{\\\\{[^}]*\\\\{\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/regex/Matcher.html#find(\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Matcher.find()<\/a>.  Trying to do this with a positive match is difficult for the same reason using <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6751105/why-its-not-possible-to-use-regex-to-parse-html-xml-a-formal-explanation-in-la\">regex against XML is problematic<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you want to grab the contents of the braces this should suffice <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\\\\{\\\\{(\\\\w+\\\\)}\\\\}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 38700012,
            "question_id": 38699926,
            "last_edit_date": 1495542156
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/IFOp5.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 4739783,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3832970,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3832970/wiktor-stribi%c5%bcew",
                "reputation": 631012,
                "display_name": "Wiktor Stribiżew"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1470059307,
            "creation_date": 1470059307,
            "body": "<p>It is not clear what you mean by \"make a pattern  more simple\". Good patterns are known to be long. A shorter regex is rarely <em>precise<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p>In your case, you should not use escaping with <code>{<\/code> and <code>}<\/code> symbols inside the character classes (you fixed that after my first comment), and you do not need lazy quantifiers inside the expression <em>unless<\/em> you are using captured values for some further processing. However, you do not seem to use them, so use:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\"^([^{}]*\\\\{\\\\{([^{}]*)\\\\}\\\\}[^{}]*)+$\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>See <a href=\"http://ideone.com/kJeHM6\" rel=\"nofollow\">Java demo<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String s = \"I have this {{example}} which is right\";\nPattern pattern = Pattern.compile(\"^([^{}]*\\\\{\\\\{([^{}]*)\\\\}\\\\}[^{}]*)+$\");\nMatcher matcher = pattern.matcher(s);\nif (matcher.matches()){\n    System.out.println(matcher.group(0)); \n} \n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 38700578,
            "question_id": 38699926
        }
    ],
